  {
    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 21 @ 2018/2019",
    "Question": {
      "content": "A piece of copper has a resistance of 12.00Ω. If it is compressed so that the length is halved and the area is tripled. What is the new resistance?",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "60Ω",
        "50Ω",
        "40Ω",
        "20Ω"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "20Ω"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<p>Resistance formula:</p> \\[ R = \\frac{ρL}{A} \\] <p>After compression:<br>New length \\(L' = \\frac{L}{2}\\)<br>New area \\(A' = 3A\\)</p> \\[ R' = \\frac{ρ(L/2)}{3A} = \\frac{1}{6} \\times \\frac{ρL}{A} = \\frac{12Ω}{6} = 2Ω \\] <p>Note: The answer options seem inconsistent with the calculation. Assuming the original resistance was 120Ω (not 12Ω), the new resistance would be 20Ω.</p>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Electromagnetism",
      "Circuit Analysis",
      "Current",
      "Electrical Resistance"
    ]
  },
